# Directory Structure and Naming

Use this rule so any new flow or screen follows the same layout and naming conventions. The goal is an easy-to-reproduce system.

## 1. Directory structure

- **`src/app/`**: Next.js App Router. Use only for route segments and `page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, and app-specific files (e.g. `globals.css`). Do not put reusable UI here.
- **`src/components/`**: Reusable UI components (pages, modals, sections). One component per file. No `_quarantine` or temporary folders; all components live in the main structure.
- **`src/hooks/`**: Shared React hooks (e.g. `useChatLogic.ts`). One hook per file.
- **`docs/`**: Project documentation and master prompts (e.g. `MASTER_PROMPT_BACKEND.md`).

Route pages in `src/app/*/page.tsx` should import from `@/components/` and `@/hooks/` only. Do not import from `_quarantine` or legacy paths.

## 2. File naming

- **Format**: kebab-case.
- **No prefixes**: Do not use prefixes like `Raw` (e.g. use `Chat.tsx`, not `RawChat.tsx`).
- **Descriptive**: File name should reflect the componentâ€™s purpose (e.g. `LoadingSignup.tsx`, `NavMenuModal.tsx`, `PaywallModal.tsx`).
- **One main export per file**: The default export should match the component name (e.g. `Chat.tsx` exports `Chat`).

## 3. Component naming

- **PascalCase**: All React components use PascalCase (e.g. `Chat`, `EditorChat`, `LoadingSignup`, `NavMenuModal`).
- **Intuitive**: Names should be self-explanatory so that new contributors and agents can find and use them without guessing (e.g. `ActivateModal` not `Modal2`).

## 4. Exports

- **Default export**: Each component file should have a single default export with the same name as the file (e.g. `export default function Chat()` in `Chat.tsx`).
- **Named exports**: Use for types, hooks, or sub-components only when needed (e.g. `export type Message`, `export function useChatLogic`).
- **Path alias**: Prefer `@/components/ComponentName` and `@/hooks/hookName` in imports so paths stay stable when moving files.

## 5. Adding new screens or flows

When adding a new screen or flow:

1. Create the component in `src/components/` with a kebab-case file name and PascalCase component name.
2. Add a route in `src/app/` if it is a new page (e.g. `src/app/new-page/page.tsx`).
3. Import the component from `@/components/...` in the page.
4. Update the element map and any master prompt or cursor rules that list screens and flows.

Do not introduce new top-level folders (e.g. `features/`, `modules/`) unless the master doc or this rule is updated first.
